It was to support tracking of landMassSize while keeping the logic self contained to the method. The other option is an anon class and have:
final int maxLandMassSize[] = new int[1];
in the method scope so that the inner class can write to maxLandMassSize[0] (since you can't write to an int. This seemed cleaner than that.

AtomicReference AFAIK is preferred way to avoid the array of size 1:
final int maxLandMassSize[] = new int[1];
There might be other solutions to be had too..

