Apologies @asvitkine if this is getting pedantic for you, just want to be sure the suggestion for how to avoid overriding concrete methods is somewhat clear so that you can respond or incorporate it.
Example of concrete method override:
class Parent {
  int computeSomething() {
       return 1;
   }
}

@Override
class Child extends Parent{
  int computeSomething() {
       return 10;
   }
}

In the above, there are really two behaviors, we can expand the inheritance tree to flatten the structure, ie instead of:
  P
    \
     C(1)

We get a graph that looks like this:
       P
     /   \
 C(1)   C(2)

That would look like this:
absract class Parent {
  abstract int computeSomething();
}

@Override
class Child1 extends Parent{
  int computeSomething() {
       return 1;
   }
}

@Override
class Child2 extends Parent{
  int computeSomething() {
       return 10;
   }
}

The other recommendation is to inject behavior via configuration, in which case there is no inheritance at all, eg:

@AllArgsBuilder
class Parent {
  private final Supplier<Integer> computation;
  int computeSomething() {
     return computation.get();
  }
}


class SomeClass {
   Parent child1 = new Parent(() -> 1);
   Parent child2 = new Parent(() -> 10);
}

